5. Specific Bugs Identified
Bug #1 — Flash of locked fields on page load (app.js)

visibleModules is [] when the synchronous render() fires on line 528, before onAuthChange has resolved and called getVisibleModules(). On an 'open' platform, every field card renders as locked (🔒, grey, non-clickable) for ~100–300 ms until Firebase resolves the auth state and triggers a second render. On slow connections this is visible.

Fix: Skip the line-528 render() call — let onAuthChange (which always fires immediately) own the first render. Or initialise visibleModules = LMS_CONFIG.modules as an optimistic default for 'open' mode.
Bug #2 — upsertUserIndex not called on sign-in (app.js)

The spec (Phase 6 shell changes) requires await upsertUserIndex(user) inside onAuthChange. It's currently absent, meaning the admin panel will show stale displayName/photoURL for any user whose Google profile changes between sessions, and will miss any email-based user who doesn't re-register.

Fix: Import upsertUserIndex from ./db.js and call it inside the if (user) block in onAuthChange.
Bug #3 — accessControl missing from registry.js

The spec requires accessControl: { mode: 'open' } as an explicit top-level field in LMS_CONFIG. It is absent from the uploaded registry.js. The system works only because all consumers default via ?? 'open'. If you ever want to deploy in 'controlled' mode, you'd need to add it anyway.

Fix: Add accessControl: { mode: 'open' } to LMS_CONFIG in registry.js.
Bug #4 — Language changes not synced to Firestore (app.js)

switchLanguage() writes to localStorage but never calls updateUserLang(uid, lang). The spec says the Firestore lang field should stay in sync. On a new device, sign-in restores the language from Firestore profile — but if the user never set it there, they always get the default.

Fix: Import updateUserLang from ./db.js; call if (currentUser) await updateUserLang(currentUser.uid, lang) inside switchLanguage().
Bug #5 — document.title not set dynamically (app.js)

The spec says app.js should set document.title = LMS_CONFIG.appName. Currently the HTML has it hardcoded. It works now because both say "LMS Platform", but changing appName in the registry won't affect the browser tab.

Fix: Add document.title = LMS_CONFIG.appName; early in app.js.
Minor — activeModuleId initialises to LMS_CONFIG.modules[0]?.id instead of null (app.js, line 42)

The spec says let activeModuleId = null. The current value ('database') is reset to null by enterField(), so it causes no visual problem when fields are defined. In backward-compat mode (no fields) the pre-selection is arguably acceptable behaviour. No urgent fix required, but it diverges from spec.

6. Unexpected Extra Files (Not in Spec)
The uploaded file list includes three files not described anywhere in Chats 1–17 or the spec:

lms/core/landing.js — claims to "drive index.html" but index.html imports app.js, not landing.js. It implements a multi-page navigation flow that goes to lms/fields/field.html. Currently unreferenced from any HTML entry point — appears to be dead code.
lms/core/field-page.js — drives lms/fields/field.html. Part of a multi-page architecture parallel to the SPA.
lms/core/module-shell.js — drives lms/modules/module.html. Also part of the multi-page architecture.

These three files form a self-consistent alternative to the SPA approach but are not wired to the root index.html. They don't break anything, but landing.js in particular is dead weight, and the multi-page approach uses localStorage-only progress (no Firestore sync), missing all Phase 4 logic. If the multi-page path was intentional you should decide which architecture to keep.

